          "body": "The first 'then' of the chapter (v.5) is stunning in what it names. After eight seeking-verbs in vv.1-4, the reader might expect 'then you will become wise' or 'then you will understand life.' Instead: 'then you will discern the fear of the LORD and discover the knowledge of God.' The goal of wisdom-seeking is not competence — it is the fear of the LORD and relational knowledge of God Himself. This reframes the entire enterprise. Wisdom is not a life-skill that produces success; it is a God-centered orientation that produces worship. The verse 6 warrant explains why this is the outcome: 'the LORD gives wisdom; from His mouth come knowledge and understanding.' All true wisdom is theocentric in origin. It is God speaking (peh, 'His mouth') that produces knowledge and understanding. The Reformers were right to see here an anticipation of the doctrine of Scripture: God's own verbal self-disclosure is the channel through which wisdom enters the human mind and heart."
